      })]
    }), "\n", _jsx(_components.p, {
      children: "Raised in Lubumbashi, Sammy Baloji has long been viscerally aware of the effects of the colonial period in modern day DRC. Lubumbashi had been a center of mining for decades with many Congolese men forced to participate as laborers in the early twentieth century.The Katanga province where Lubumbashi lies is rich in natural resources that were exploited by the Belgian king during Congo’s colonial rule. The industry had brought great prosperity to Lubumbashi but was abandoned in the post-colonial era when Baloji was born. His work has often been inspired by the circumstances of Lubumbashi and the DRC’s colonial history as he excavates the meanings of social identity and cultural memory."
    }), "\n", _jsx(_components.p, {
      children: "Baloji’s practice extends across multiple media, most particularly photography with an emphasis on questions of the archive, pointing to his persistent interest in history as artistic subject. His work is often informed by his research into Congo’s past and incorporates his findings in the archives. Underpinning his art is this basic motivation as explained by Baloji himself: “I’m not interested in colonialism as nostalgia, or in it as a thing of the past, but in the continuation of that system.”"
    }), "\n", _jsx(_components.p, {
      children: "Perhaps his most famous series, Mémoire (2004-2006), comprises 29 images that juxtapose Lubumbashi’s colonial past with its complicated present. In this series, Baloji superimposes old archival photos of mine workers with colorful shots of modern Lubumbashi featuring the discarded ruins of industrial structures and the rubble they left behind. The figures are ghostly and seem to haunt the landscape that they now inhabit. In Untitled 17, we are confronted with such a ghost - a shirtless man in black-and-white stares direclty out of the picture plane. The metal scaffolding of Baloji’s own photograph lead the eye directly to his face. A few other small figures populate the background, roaming through the industrial wastes for any valuable vestige left behind. The landscape is barren and does little to represent the prosperity that Katanga once enjoyed. Baloji seems to ask: the mines were successful during the colonial era, but at what cost and to what end? The nameless central figure’s labor has led to what we see now. Baloji speaks starkly to the deleterious effects of colonial exploitation and capitalism."
    }), "\n", _jsx(_components.p, {
      children: "His photographic practice with his interest in archival absences speaks directly to Lydia’s own production during her journey. She brought with her over 600 pounds of photography and videography gear. Extant receipts demonstrate that she was sending off the film and having it developed in real time during her trip. Yet her work only fed the absences that Baloji now seeks to redress."
